I use a quite simple WHITESPACE_ONLY compilation level. There is a nice check whether the browser is Internet Explorer. I use it wide in my JS scripts:

var isIE = '\v'=='v';

After compilation with Google Closure Compiler we have:

var isIE=&quot;\u000b&quot;==&quot;v&quot;;

and the check doesn't work. I know about ASCII output and reg. expressions which should be splitted with string concatenation. But the statement above is not a reg. expression. Why does \v get replaced by \u000b at all? Do you have a workaround for me? Is it a bug?

Many thanks in advance.
